Often overlooked in programs, or due to the simplistic and repetitive nature skipped by athletes.

Don’t overlook the Double Contact. 

When progressing athletes to more advanced jump and plyometric exercises, using double contacts can be a fantastic bridging option. 

In this example the double contact allows the athlete to momentarily reset to find a far better position to utilise the SSC whilst also taking away some of the horizontal momentum, allowing to redirect the force more vertically. 

The cue we used here was on the second contact to really “attack” the ground. 

Once consistent rhythm and timing is established, we’ll take away the double contact and move onto continuous jumps. 

See here in Video 1 (set 3 after taking the continuous action away and implementing the double contact) vs Video 2 (set 2 and introducing the double contact) before to see the instant difference not only in the movement but the athlete’s overall confidence. (Note we’d still like to minimise the forward jump on the first contact)

Neural Priming Session for Football 

Neural Priming/ Potentiation session can be used 12-48 hours prior to the start of competition and has shown to have a hormonal and arousal response in athletes. 

The concept is expose athletes to max force (generally without or limited eccentric portion) or max velocity movements and can highly individualised to the athlete. Typically the session duration short, intensity high and volume low. 

Here’s an example for an soccer athlete:

V2: Hop to Box + Tuck

Variability vs Load: The Youth Athlete
The youth athlete is unique as we want to build a large base of movement capacity and quality, then layering load over time. 

With youth athletes, the window of adaptation is so large that any subtle change in stimulus will result in strength and motor control gains while also keeping training interesting and fun. 

Understanding and implementing these principles is the key to long term development of youth athletes while ensuring the fundamentals of movement literacy developed through a variety of movement patterns, planes of motion and loads. 

These can provide challenging progressions looking at movement literacy and variability vs load.

Progressing Your Lateral Chain 

The Lateral Chain is an important aspect of athletic development- both capacity and strength. 

How well an athlete can control and create lateral flexion through the trunk and hips is crucial for performance, including high speed running, cutting, fending etc. 

Quite often we tend to lean towards low load capacity based work such as Side Planks or Pallof Press variations. Just like all movements, there’s a place for exercises on the progression/ regression continuum- it’s our job to select the right exercise for the right adaptations. 

Here’s some moderate to advanced options that can be incorporated into your current program as accessory or resilience based. 

Exercise 1: A Position OH Plate Lateral Flexion

Exercise 2: Lateral GHR Iso Hold + OH Plate Press

Exercise 3: Standing Banded OH Lateral Flexion

Exploring TRUE Unilateral Strength For Youth 

It’s important to understand the difference between a true unilateral (single limb) and a unilateral oriented movements. 

Unilateral oriented is where majority of the weight is supported on a single limb and the other limb is acting as a support limb for balance, stability etc. Whereas true unilateral is a single limb lever throughout the entire movement. 

The benefits of using either of these movement options, such as Step Ups, compared to a Bilateral Position is isolating movement compensations, stability, variability and improve movement patterns.

In the youth setting, these can provide challenging progressions looking at movement literacy and variability vs load. 

Here are some examples of true Uni Lateral exercises 
Video 1 - Skater Squat + Plate Counterbalance
Video 2 - Skater Squat (Vest Loaded) 
Video 3 - Banded Assisted Pistol Squat 
Video 4 - TRX Assisted Pistol Squat 
Video 5 - Plate Counterbalance Step Down

Banded Options For Low Amp Plyometrics

Here’s a few options to modify some of our Low Amplitude Plyometric options - often one of the biggest “gap fillers” in our athletes program, especially those looking to shift towards being more reactive. 

Adding banded tension across the shoulders (load can be increased by increased band tension) requires far greater pre tension and reactivity with the ground vs traditional body weight pogo variations. These pair nicely with more intensive jump options such as Hurdle Jumps or Double Contact options such as DC Hurdle Jumps or DC Hops. 

Another option is adding banded tension in a variety of lines of pull is a great way add a different stimulus to traditional pogo variations while still building capacity and tendentious qualities of the lower shank/ foot through different angles. 

The bands tweak traditional pogos by:

The front and rear require more force into the ground and expose the athlete to greater pretension to hold the same postures due to the speed of the movement. 

The lateral pull exposes the athlete to the frontal plane and the lateral vector.

Challenging The Midline 

These challenge the demands of the midline in different ways. 

Adding a lateral movement to an Ab Wheel (which by increasing the angle will also increase the difficulty) challenges the athletes ability to hold a strong midline position. 

The single leg roll out requires far more control at the hips, requiring the ability to resist rotating. 

The weight vest on an Ab Wheel requires extra control throughout the entirety of the movement, particularly at range. 

Without throwing the baby out with the bath water, change for the sake of change can certainly be detrimental to the success of a program, however little variations can be key to athlete buy in and consistency in the long run - especially for the highly trained athlete.

Hamstring Switch Variations 

Here a two variations of Bosch Hamstring Switches - to expose the distal aspect of the Hamstrings to high velocities. 

These are two good options to expose the athlete to the catch position with high eccentric force. A key coaching point I like is to ensure the  lumbar pelvic is in a stable position in each catch - minimising any extension. 

The action should be switching down towards the ground vs popping up into the air. Aim to keep the feet straight to ensure to load the medial portion of the Hamstring (a lot of athletes will try to avoid this position by externally rotating the feet) 

It’s important to note these form only a small portion of an athletes overall program. For hamstring targeted strength specifically these doesn’t replace meat and potatoes (proximal and distal load) or high speed sprinting.

Step Ups as a movement option can be adapted for high load (strength), low load (speed), position standard (stable less specific position) Hip Lock/ A Frame (stability more specific position) and initiation such as Drop Step (stiffness) etc.

Exploring True Unilateral Strength 

It’s important to understand the difference between a true unilateral (single limb) and a unilateral oriented movements. 

Unilateral oriented is where majority of the weight is supported on a single limb and the other limb is acting as a support limb for balance, stability etc. Whereas true unilateral is a single limb lever throughout the entire movement. 

The benefits of using either of these movement options, such as Step Ups, compared to a Bilateral Position is isolating movement compensations, stability, variability and improve movement patterns.

There’s nothing more impressive than banging out a set of Pistol Squats or Skater Squats - here’s how you get there:

Progressing Your Core Training 

The trunk is an important aspect of athletic development - both capacity and strength. 

How well an athlete can control and create flexion through the trunk and hips is crucial for performance, including high speed running, cutting, fending etc. 

Quite often we tend to lean towards low load capacity based work such as Planks or Side Planks. 

Just like all movements, there’s a place for exercises on the progression/ regression continuum - it’s our job to select the right exercise for the right adaptations. 

Here’s some moderate to advanced options that can be incorporated into your current program as accessory or resilience based. 

Exercise 1: Body Saw

Exercise 2: Stability Ball Stir Pots

Loading Low Amp Plyometrics

Here’s a few options to modify some of our Low Amplitude Plyometric options - often one of the biggest “gap fillers” in our athletes program, especially those looking to shift towards being more reactive. 

Adding banded tension across the shoulders (load can be increased by increased band tension) requires far greater pre tension and reactivity with the ground vs traditional body weight pogo variations. They can also be used to assist in movement, for decrease in ground contact time and increasing relative stiffness. 

Another option is adding banded tension in a variety of lines of pull is a great way add a different stimulus to traditional pogo variations while still building capacity and tendentious qualities of the lower shank/ foot through different angles. (Not shown) 

Finally the use of external load such as a medicine ball or plate, as this can challenge not only the system through load but also centre of mass and body position (plate over head vs in front of body, vs med ball etc)

When programming for the youth athlete, rather than always looking at absolute load (ie weight lifted) there are several key ways we can progress, regress and lateralise movement. 

These include:

- Change in lever 
- Change in implement (DB, Corebags, Medball, BB etc) 
- Manipulating the tempo
- Combination movements (eg Step Up to A Position)

Building The Bosch Hold 

Implementing unloaded and loaded, short duration (3-10secs) to long duration (20-30secs) hip isometrics for angle specificity, strength, capacity relation to run specific positions. 

The resistive forces are applied in the apposing direction to counteract gravitational forces in a set position. These exercises target the hamstring under yielding isometric conditions, where muscle tension is created without any change in joint angle or muscle length. Isometric holds are normally sub-maximal in nature due to stability issues and time constraints. 

These are a great tool for rehab or performance ticking time under tension, length tension relationship, reducing residual fatigue, motor control and high outputs. 

Here are a few variations used for a variety of adaptations to the individual athletes needs.

Here are 2 of the most common tests used for jump profiling to gain objective data as part of initial and ongoing testing protocols using @vald_performance with Head of Sports Science @adamwyli3 

Countermovement Jump (CMJ) 
Used to measure an athletes lower body power, the ability to utilise SSC (stretch shortening cycle) and monitor performance/ readiness. 

Squat Jump (SJ) 
Used to measure an athletes explosive power (speed-strength), the ability during slow SSC/ low stretch loads and can be compared against the Incremental Drop Jump Test. 

From these jumps, we can calculate the athletes EUR (Eccentric Utilisation Ratio) as a basis for programming specific Plyometric options where we look at the ratio between the flight (cm) an athlete’s CMJ and SJ.

Performance Target:
As a general rule we look to target an EUR between 1.15 - 1.25. Going below this range, the goal would be to develop their SSC to further enhance their elasticity. 

If they go too far the other way where they lack the ability to produce force through their jumps. Their performance target would be to improve their maximal strength and force output. 

Summary:
Eccentric Utilisation Ratio only forms part of the performance puzzle. And even athletes in the target zone should still be working on these pieces to further enhance their performance demands of their sport.

Constraints based learning for LTAD. 

When coaching Youth Athletes there can be nothing more frustrating than trying to learn a new movement or skill and the athletes “just not getting it.”

As coaches, if we have some simple tools in our kit to help make the learning process easier, it makes for a much more enjoyable experience for both the coach and athlete. 

When discussing movement literacy, Youth Athletes are encouraged to fail (provided it’s a safe environment) and all reps don’t have to be the perfect textbook movement. It’s about encouraging them to fail, but having solutions to help with addressing the problem. 

Here are a few examples of constraints based approach to let the athlete feel what the correct pattern should be:

Progressing The Paloff Press In Rehab/ Return To Sport - Wide Stance. 

The Paloff Press is a staple low level, low/mod load anti rotation trunk movement by and large used for trunk stiffness and the ability/ awareness to resist rotation from the midline.

Putting the Long in LTAD
The youth athlete is unique as we want to build a large base of movement capacity and quality, then layering load over time. 

With youth athletes, the window of adaptation is so large that any subtle change in stimulus will result in strength and motor control gains while also keeping training interesting and fun. 

Understanding and implementing these principles is the key to long term development of youth athletes while ensuring the fundamentals of movement literacy developed through a variety of movement patterns, planes of motion and loads. 

These can provide challenging progressions looking at movement literacy and variability vs load. 

Another key thing to remember is if we are truely focused on LONG TERM athletic development, in time these athletes will have so little variability as they progress, so don’t over look the ability to build such a large base.
